06751nam a22009975i 9781501503757DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20162016gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)958055282  a97815015037577 a10.1515/97815015037572doi  a(DE-B1597)460340  a(OCoLC)954046442  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP99.4.P78bT495 2016 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a302.2/01922300aThinking with Diagrams :bThe Semiotic Basis of Human Cognition /ced. by Sybille Krämer, Christina Ljungberg. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (V, 247 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSemiotics, Communication and Cognition [SCC] ,x1867-0873 ;v1700tFrontmatter -- tTable of contents -- tThinking and diagrams – An introduction -- tI. What is a diagram and how does it function? -- t1. On the “thing-ness” of diagrams -- t2. The role of diagrams in abductive reasoning -- t3. Behind the diagrams: cognitive issues and open problems -- t4. Diagrammatic problem solving -- t5. Is there a general diagram concept? -- t6. The diagrammatic nature of maps -- tII. Diagrammatic scenes -- t7. Is there a diagrammatic impulse with Plato? ‘Quasi-diagrammatic-scenes’ in Plato’s philosophy -- t8. The diagram as board game: Semiotic discoveries in Alfonso the Wise’s Book of Games (1283 CE) – with some observations as to Gudea as Architect (2000 BCE) -- t9. Pattern language and space syntax: Alexander, Chomsky, Peirce and Wittgenstein -- tReferences -- tIndex of names -- tIndex of subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiagrammatic reasoning is crucial for human cognition. It is hard to think of any forms of science or knowledge without the "intermediary world" of diagrams and diagrammatic representation in thought experiments and/or processes, manifested in forms as divers as notes, tables, schemata, graphs, drawings and maps. Despite their phenomenological and structural-functional differences, these forms of representation share a number of important attributes and epistemic functions. Combining aspects of linguistic and pictorial symbolism, diagrams go beyond the traditional distinction between language and image. They do not only represent, yet intervene in what is represented. Their spatiality, materiality and operativity establish a dynamic tool to exteriorize thinking, thus contributing to the idea of the extended mind. They foster imagination and problem solving, facilitate orientation in knowledge spaces and the discovery of unsuspected relationships. How can the diagrammatic nature of cognitive and knowledge practices be theorized historically as well as systematically? This is what this volume explores by investigating the semiotic dimension of diagrams as to knowledge, information and reasoning, e.g., the 'thing-ness' of diagrams in the history of art, the range of diagrammatic reasoning in logic, mathematics, philosophy and the sciences in general, including the knowledge function of maps.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCognition. 0aSemioticsxPsychological aspects. 0aSigns and symbolsxPsychological aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognition.  aDiagrams.  aSemiotics.1 aBauer, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBogen, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiardino, Valeria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrämer, Sybille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrämer, Sybille, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLjungberg, Christina, econtribut